<BaseLayout title="Axolotl Care Guide" description="Learn how to care for an axolotl: habitat, diet, health, and legal considerations.">
  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-4">Axolotl Care Guide</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">Axolotls are aquatic salamanders native to Mexico, known for their regenerative abilities. They require cool, clean water and minimal light.</p>
  <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-2">Habitat</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">Provide a tank of at least 20 gallons with a secure lid. Maintain water temperature between 60–68°F. Use a gentle filter and hideouts.</p>
  <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-2">Diet</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">Feed a varied diet of earthworms, bloodworms, and high-quality pellets. Avoid live fish to prevent disease transmission.</p>
  <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-2">Health</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">Monitor for fungal infections or stress. Avoid handling and perform regular water changes to maintain quality.</p>
  <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-2">Legality</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">Axolotls are restricted in certain US states (e.g., California, New Jersey). Check local laws in the <a href="/laws/new-jersey" class="text-primary font-bold underline">Legality section</a>.</p>
